TY  - JOUR
AU  - Barlevy, Gadi
AU  - Veronesi, Pietro
T1  - Information Acquisition in Financial Markets
PY  - 2000
Y1  - 2000/01/01
DO  - 10.1111/1467-937X.00122
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 67
IS  - 1
SP  - 79
EP  - 90
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Previous work on information and financial markets has focused on a special set of assumptions: agents have exponential utility, and random variables are normally distributed. These assumptions are often necessary to obtain closed-form solutions. We present an example with alternative assumptions, and demonstrate that some of the conclusions from previous literature fail to hold. In particular, we show that in our example, as more agents acquire information, prices do not necessarily become more informative, and agents may have greater incentive to acquire information. Learning can therefore be a strategic complement, allowing for the possibility of multiple equilibria.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1467-937X.00122
ER  - 



